{"type":"text","timestamp":1778982054385,"sessionID":"ses_1cc697c48ffeRmAX4IVRPP82Ku","part":{"id":"prt_e3397d958001M13lsrQFAntvhh","messageID":"msg_e3397ceb20016uYVq5q1uAsjgn","sessionID":"ses_1cc697c48ffeRmAX4IVRPP82Ku","type":"text","text":"The chemistry and reference side checks out: PMID `16957230` matches the substrate-specific enzyme, and `CHEBI:55534` is the acid form named in the issue. I’m pulling a couple of ontology precedents for obsolete MF terms so the replacement metadata matches house style before I edit.","time":{"start":1778982050136,"end":1778982054383}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778982054427,"sessionID":"ses_1cc697c48ffeRmAX4IVRPP82Ku","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_GuwIdQWybbTWY1jMpHPW8TKa","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_16957230.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/references_cache/PMID_16957230.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: reference_id: PMID:16957230\n3: title: Characterization of (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate dehydrogenase and a family III coenzyme A transferase involved in reduction of L-leucine to isocaproate by Clostridium difficile.\n4: authors:\n5: - Kim J\n6: - Darley D\n7: - Selmer T\n8: - Buckel W\n9: journal: Appl Environ Microbiol\n10: year: '2006'\n11: doi: 10.1128/AEM.00772-06\n12: keywords:\n13: - \"Alcohol Oxidoreductases/chemistry, genetics, metabolism\"\n14: - Amino Acid Sequence\n15: - Base Sequence\n16: - Caproates/metabolism\n17: - Catalytic Domain/genetics\n18: - \"Cloning, Molecular\"\n19: - \"Clostridioides difficile/enzymology, genetics, metabolism, pathogenicity\"\n20: - \"Coenzyme A-Transferases/antagonists & inhibitors, classification, genetics, metabolism\"\n21: - \"DNA, Bacterial/genetics\"\n22: - \"Genes, Bacterial\"\n23: - Humans\n24: - Kinetics\n25: - Leucine/metabolism\n26: - Molecular Sequence Data\n27: - \"Mutagenesis, Site-Directed\"\n28: - Oxidation-Reduction\n29: - \"Recombinant Proteins/genetics, metabolism\"\n30: - \"Sequence Homology, Amino Acid\"\n31: - \"Spectrometry, Mass, Matrix-Assisted Laser Desorption-Ionization\"\n32: - Substrate Specificity\n33: content_type: abstract_only\n34: ---\n35: \n36: # Characterization of (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate dehydrogenase and a family III coenzyme A transferase involved in reduction of L-leucine to isocaproate by Clostridium difficile.\n37: **Authors:** Kim J, Darley D, Selmer T, Buckel W\n38: **Journal:** Appl Environ Microbiol (2006)\n39: **DOI:** [10.1128/AEM.00772-06](https://doi.org/10.1128/AEM.00772-06)\n40: \n41: ## Content\n42: \n43: 1. Appl Environ Microbiol. 2006 Sep;72(9):6062-9. doi: 10.1128/AEM.00772-06.\n44: \n45: Characterization of (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate dehydrogenase and a family III \n46: coenzyme A transferase involved in reduction of L-leucine to isocaproate by \n47: Clostridium difficile.\n48: \n49: Kim J(1), Darley D, Selmer T, Buckel W.\n50: \n51: Author information:\n52: (1)Laboratorium für Mikrobiologie, Fachbereich Biologie, Philipps-Universität, \n53: D-35032 Marburg, Germany. buckel@staff.uni-marburg.de.\n54: \n55: The strictly anaerobic pathogenic bacterium Clostridium difficile occurs in the \n56: human gut and is able to thrive from fermentation of leucine. Thereby the amino \n57: acid is both oxidized to isovalerate plus CO(2) and reduced to isocaproate. In \n58: the reductive branch of this pathway, the dehydration of \n59: (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproyl-coenzyme A (CoA) to (E)-2-isocaprenoyl-CoA is probably \n60: catalyzed via radical intermediates. The dehydratase requires activation by an \n61: ATP-dependent one-electron transfer (J. Kim, D. Darley, and W. Buckel, FEBS J. \n62: 272:550-561, 2005). Prior to the dehydration, a dehydrogenase and a CoA \n63: transferase are supposed to be involved in the formation of \n64: (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproyl-CoA. Deduced amino acid sequences of ldhA and hadA from \n65: the genome of C. difficile showed high identities to d-lactate dehydrogenase and \n66: family III CoA transferase, respectively. Both putative genes encoding the \n67: dehydrogenase and CoA transferase were cloned and overexpressed in Escherichia \n68: coli; the recombinant Strep tag II fusion proteins were purified to homogeneity \n69: and characterized. The substrate specificity of the monomeric LdhA (36.5 kDa) \n70: indicated that 2-oxoisocaproate (K(m) = 68 muM, k(cat) = 31 s(-1)) and NADH were \n71: the native substrates. For the reverse reaction, the enzyme accepted (R)- but \n72: not (S)-2-hydroxyisocaproate and therefore was named (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate \n73: dehydrogenase. HadA showed CoA transferase activity with \n74: (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproyl-CoA as a donor and isocaproate or (E)-2-isocaprenoate as \n75: an acceptor. By site-directed mutagenesis, the conserved D171 was identified as \n76: an essential catalytic residue probably involved in the formation of a mixed \n77: anhydride with the acyl group of the thioester substrate. However, neither \n78: hydroxylamine nor sodium borohydride, both of which are inactivators of the CoA \n79: transferase, modified this residue. The dehydrogenase and the CoA transferase \n80: fit well into the proposed pathway of leucine reduction to isocaproate.\n81: \n82: DOI: 10.1128/AEM.00772-06\n83: PMCID: PMC1563608\n84: PMID: 16957230 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n\n(End of file - total 84 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nreference_id: PMID:16957230\ntitle: Characterization of (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate dehydrogenase and a family III coenzyme A transferase involved in reduction of L-leucine to isocaproate by Clostridium difficile.\nauthors:\n- Kim J\n- Darley D\n- Selmer T\n- Buckel W\njournal: Appl Environ Microbiol\nyear: '2006'\ndoi: 10.1128/AEM.00772-06\nkeywords:\n- \"Alcohol Oxidoreductases/chemistry, genetics, metabolism\"\n- Amino Acid Sequence\n- Base Sequence\n- Caproates/metabolism\n- Catalytic Domain/genetics\n- \"Cloning, Molecular\"\n- \"Clostridioides difficile/enzymology, genetics, metabolism, pathogenicity\"\n- \"Coenzyme A-Transferases/antagonists & inhibitors, classification, genetics, metabolism\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"references_cache/PMID_16957230.md","time":{"start":1778982054373,"end":1778982054425}},"id":"prt_e3397e9da001Ew5wAaWHkbKyxO","sessionID":"ses_1cc697c48ffeRmAX4IVRPP82Ku","messageID":"msg_e3397ceb20016uYVq5q1uAsjgn"}}
