{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778982131233,"sessionID":"ses_1cc697c48ffeRmAX4IVRPP82Ku","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_7ucg3fGD33sS2L3RpKUK90rZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: RESEARCH.md\n+## Issue #31966 research summary\n+\n+The requested change is to obsolete `GO:0043713` `(R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate dehydrogenase activity` and replace it with `GO:0140175` `(2R)-2-hydroxyacid dehydrogenase (NAD+) activity`.\n+\n+Observations:\n+\n+- `GO:0043713` has no internal ontology usages beyond its own stanza.\n+- `runoak -i amigo: associations GO:0043713` returned no direct annotations.\n+- `GO:0140175` already carries `EC:1.1.1.345` as an exact match and `RHEA:10052` as a narrow match, which covers the substrate-specific reaction discussed in the issue.\n+- `CHEBI:55534` is `(R)-2-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid`, matching the issue discussion around `(R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate`; the corresponding RHEA participant name is the conjugate base form.\n+\n+## PMID:16957230 \"Characterization of (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate dehydrogenase and a family III coenzyme A transferase involved in reduction of L-leucine to isocaproate by Clostridium difficile\"\n+\n+The source publication validates that the historical term describes a substrate-specific instance of a broader `(2R)-2-hydroxyacid dehydrogenase (NAD+)` activity.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:16957230 \"The substrate specificity of the monomeric LdhA (36.5 kDa) indicated that 2-oxoisocaproate (K(m) = 68 muM, k(cat) = 31 s(-1)) and NADH were the native substrates. For the reverse reaction, the enzyme accepted (R)- but not (S)-2-hydroxyisocaproate and therefore was named (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate dehydrogenase.\"\n+    - The enzyme is stereospecific for the R/2R substrate.\n+    - The chemistry is a specific case of the broader EC/RHEA-backed activity already represented by `GO:0140175`.\n+    - This supports direct replacement rather than retention of a separate GO class.\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA RESEARCH.md","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,19 @@\n+## Issue #31966 research summary\n+\n+The requested change is to obsolete `GO:0043713` `(R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate dehydrogenase activity` and replace it with `GO:0140175` `(2R)-2-hydroxyacid dehydrogenase (NAD+) activity`.\n+\n+Observations:\n+\n+- `GO:0043713` has no internal ontology usages beyond its own stanza.\n+- `runoak -i amigo: associations GO:0043713` returned no direct annotations.\n+- `GO:0140175` already carries `EC:1.1.1.345` as an exact match and `RHEA:10052` as a narrow match, which covers the substrate-specific reaction discussed in the issue.\n+- `CHEBI:55534` is `(R)-2-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid`, matching the issue discussion around `(R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate`; the corresponding RHEA participant name is the conjugate base form.\n+\n+## PMID:16957230 \"Characterization of (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate dehydrogenase and a family III coenzyme A transferase involved in reduction of L-leucine to isocaproate by Clostridium difficile\"\n+\n+The source publication validates that the historical term describes a substrate-specific instance of a broader `(2R)-2-hydroxyacid dehydrogenase (NAD+)` activity.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:16957230 \"The substrate specificity of the monomeric LdhA (36.5 kDa) indicated that 2-oxoisocaproate (K(m) = 68 muM, k(cat) = 31 s(-1)) and NADH were the native substrates. For the reverse reaction, the enzyme accepted (R)- but not (S)-2-hydroxyisocaproate and therefore was named (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate dehydrogenase.\"\n+    - The enzyme is stereospecific for the R/2R substrate.\n+    - The chemistry is a specific case of the broader EC/RHEA-backed activity already represented by `GO:0140175`.\n+    - This supports direct replacement rather than retention of a separate GO class.\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md","relativePath":"RESEARCH.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n===================================================================\n--- /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n+++ /__w/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go/RESEARCH.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,19 @@\n+## Issue #31966 research summary\n+\n+The requested change is to obsolete `GO:0043713` `(R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate dehydrogenase activity` and replace it with `GO:0140175` `(2R)-2-hydroxyacid dehydrogenase (NAD+) activity`.\n+\n+Observations:\n+\n+- `GO:0043713` has no internal ontology usages beyond its own stanza.\n+- `runoak -i amigo: associations GO:0043713` returned no direct annotations.\n+- `GO:0140175` already carries `EC:1.1.1.345` as an exact match and `RHEA:10052` as a narrow match, which covers the substrate-specific reaction discussed in the issue.\n+- `CHEBI:55534` is `(R)-2-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid`, matching the issue discussion around `(R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate`; the corresponding RHEA participant name is the conjugate base form.\n+\n+## PMID:16957230 \"Characterization of (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate dehydrogenase and a family III coenzyme A transferase involved in reduction of L-leucine to isocaproate by Clostridium difficile\"\n+\n+The source publication validates that the historical term describes a substrate-specific instance of a broader `(2R)-2-hydroxyacid dehydrogenase (NAD+)` activity.\n+\n+* SUPPORT: PMID:16957230 \"The substrate specificity of the monomeric LdhA (36.5 kDa) indicated that 2-oxoisocaproate (K(m) = 68 muM, k(cat) = 31 s(-1)) and NADH were the native substrates. For the reverse reaction, the enzyme accepted (R)- but not (S)-2-hydroxyisocaproate and therefore was named (R)-2-hydroxyisocaproate dehydrogenase.\"\n+    - The enzyme is stereospecific for the R/2R substrate.\n+    - The chemistry is a specific case of the broader EC/RHEA-backed activity already represented by `GO:0140175`.\n+    - This supports direct replacement rather than retention of a separate GO class.\n","additions":19,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA RESEARCH.md","time":{"start":1778982131222,"end":1778982131230}},"id":"prt_e3398f103001BLOvMQikjZYOov","sessionID":"ses_1cc697c48ffeRmAX4IVRPP82Ku","messageID":"msg_e3398ec470016Kr7waEF9NPL1r"}}
